by Warren Buffett, Benjamin

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:12.700
Graham, John Templeton.

00:44:12.700 --> 00:44:13.870
Those are my heroes.

00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:16.810
I've read almost anything
that they've written.

00:44:16.810 --> 00:44:21.130
And they have had a very
dramatic impact on my way

00:44:21.130 --> 00:44:26.350
of thinking, on Harris
Associates, and Oakmark.

00:44:26.350 --> 00:44:30.730
I think value
managers especially

00:44:30.730 --> 00:44:33.410
tend not to go a lot
broader than that.

00:44:33.410 --> 00:44:36.880
And to me, that's a mistake.

00:44:36.880 --> 00:44:39.920
After you've read a few
books about Warren Buffett,

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:42.985
and you read the next
book, and maybe you

00:44:42.985 --> 00:44:45.850
learn what his breakfast
habits are, or what TV shows

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:49.390
he likes, but you really
have the foundation

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:52.550
for what's made him a
successful investor already.

00:44:52.550 --> 00:44:53.907
And it's like comfort food.

00:44:53.907 --> 00:44:55.490
You know it's not
really good for you,

00:44:55.490 --> 00:44:57.906
but there's something about
reading another Warren Buffett

00:44:57.906 --> 00:45:01.420
book that makes you feel
good as a value investor.

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:07.366
And the investors who are
very different than us,

00:45:07.366 --> 00:45:11.720
I tend not to want to emulate
their style of investing.

00:45:11.720 --> 00:45:14.140
But I find I learn
more when I read books

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:16.660
about some of the
great hedge fund

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:21.520
managers, a Paul Tudor Jones,
and Michael Steinhardt, George

00:45:21.520 --> 00:45:23.230
Soros.

00:45:23.230 --> 00:45:28.670
And there's not nearly the
overlap of the circles,

00:45:28.670 --> 00:45:31.850
like Berkshire Hathaway, and
the way we differ from them,

00:45:31.850 --> 00:45:34.340
I mean there are
differences at the edges,

00:45:34.340 --> 00:45:38.730
but it's a very similar
thought process.

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:40.760
The circle with
Michael Steinhardt

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:44.600
still overlaps, but
it's not nearly as much.

00:45:44.600 --> 00:45:49.400
And I've never read a book about
one of those great investors

00:45:49.400 --> 00:45:51.530
who weren't value
investors that hasn't

00:45:51.530 --> 00:45:56.300
made me think about some detail
of our investing process.

00:45:56.300 --> 00:46:00.320
For example, Mike Steinhardt
was famous for never wanting

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:04.280
to make an investment until
he'd sat down with the person he

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:06.950
thought was the smartest
bear on the stock

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:08.325
and understood their case.

00:46:10.900 --> 00:46:14.260
We try to do that in our
process at Oakmark, by whenever

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:16.780
somebody is presenting
a new idea to us,

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:20.110
we assign the task to
someone of saying your job

00:46:20.110 --> 00:46:22.180
is to now come into
the room and explain

00:46:22.180 --> 00:46:24.040
why this person is wrong.

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:27.460
And we want you to argue to the
best of your ability to prevent

00:46:27.460 --> 00:46:29.680
us from making this investment.

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:33.850
And hearing the two sides
argue with each other

00:46:33.850 --> 00:46:36.010
is a much more
productive atmosphere

00:46:36.010 --> 00:46:38.620
for learning about an
investment than just

00:46:38.620 --> 00:46:40.570
hearing the bullish case.

00:46:40.570 --> 00:46:42.670
Paul Tudor Jones,
there's a famous picture

00:46:42.670 --> 00:46:47.290
of him sitting at
his desk, and pinned

00:46:47.290 --> 00:46:49.000
on to the bulletin
board behind him

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:53.170
is a sign that says
losers average losers.

00:46:53.170 --> 00:46:57.340
How many times have you
heard a value investor say

00:46:57.340 --> 00:47:00.880
the stock's down 20% today, but
my estimate of business value

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:02.140
is only down 10%.

00:47:02.140 --> 00:47:06.130
So it's really cheaper
today than it was yesterday.

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:10.640
One of the great things
about data analysis

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:13.780
having become so cheap,
and us having the history

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:16.350
that we have, it's really easy
to analyze our own history now

00:47:16.350 --> 00:47:20.170
and be more data driven in
our own decision making.

00:47:20.170 --> 00:47:23.530
And we can look at and say, OK,
we've got 20 years of history

00:47:23.530 --> 00:47:27.040
here, about 130 stocks
on our approved list,

00:47:27.040 --> 00:47:28.990
what happened when this
fundamental started

00:47:28.990 --> 00:47:31.330
to deviate from what
the analysts suggested,

00:47:31.330 --> 00:47:33.435
were those good
opportunities to add.

00:47:33.435 --> 00:47:34.810
And we looked at
it and said, you

00:47:34.810 --> 00:47:38.560
know what, that was really
more of an indication

00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:41.110
that we were off
base in our analysis,

00:47:41.110 --> 00:47:43.120
and it was going to
get worse after that,

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:45.220
before it got better.

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:49.680
And adding some
guardrails to our process,

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:53.190
of saying when things
start to go negative

00:47:53.190 --> 00:47:54.741
on the fundamental story--

00:47:54.741 --> 00:47:56.490
we don't ever want to
be the investor that

00:47:56.490 --> 00:48:00.580
says if the stock falls
20% it's an automatic sale.

00:48:00.580 --> 00:48:03.990
But if the fundamentals start
to deviate, and the story isn't

00:48:03.990 --> 00:48:05.820
playing out the way
we thought it would,

00:48:05.820 --> 00:48:09.150
the fundamental story,
we want to increase

00:48:09.150 --> 00:48:12.120
the pressure on the
analysis, to make

00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:15.240
sure more people in the
firm are thinking about it,

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:17.970
forcing more meetings
with the management team,

00:48:17.970 --> 00:48:21.680
forcing more of a devil's
advocate thought process,

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:24.660
with the idea that one of
the most productive ways we

00:48:24.660 --> 00:48:27.605
can add to our performance is to
get rid of our losers earlier.

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:31.760
I get teased.

00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:36.340
We're not momentum investors
by any way, shape, or form.

00:48:36.340 --> 00:48:39.920
But I do believe there is such
a thing as fundamental momentum,

00:48:39.920 --> 00:48:42.210
that companies that
are performing well

00:48:42.210 --> 00:48:44.520
are more likely to
continue performing well,

00:48:44.520 --> 00:48:46.810
and companies that
are performing poorly

00:48:46.810 --> 00:48:48.944
are more likely to
continue poorly.

00:48:48.944 --> 00:48:50.860
SAURABH MADAAN: Newton's
first laws of motion.

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:51.650
BILL NYGREN: Yes.

00:48:51.650 --> 00:48:54.420
So it's not a new concept,
but at Oakmark, it's

00:48:54.420 --> 00:48:56.820
applying something that's
thousands of years old.

00:48:59.450 --> 00:49:02.510
So you can take these nuggets--

00:49:02.510 --> 00:49:05.210
George Soros, with his
theory of reflexivity,

00:49:05.210 --> 00:49:08.750
which was written up in
a book hundreds of pages

00:49:08.750 --> 00:49:11.330
long that I find very
difficult to follow.

00:49:11.330 --> 00:49:14.960
But way, way
oversimplified, says

00:49:14.960 --> 00:49:18.980
that what's going on
emotionally in investors

00:49:18.980 --> 00:49:21.890
can actually influence
the real economy.

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:26.660
And that psychology has a
real effect on the economy.

00:49:26.660 --> 00:49:31.670
And when direction changes,
a simple psychological change

00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:36.540
can be enough to bring about
a real change in the economy.

00:49:36.540 --> 00:49:41.070
When you go through tough
cycles like '08 and '09--

00:49:41.070 --> 00:49:44.330
and people are
always saying, sure,

00:49:44.330 --> 00:49:46.790
if things get back to normal,
then everything out there

00:49:46.790 --> 00:49:48.960
is really cheap, and
the names you own

00:49:48.960 --> 00:49:51.860
would be the right
basket of names to own.

00:49:51.860 --> 00:49:55.700
But what can ever change
to make things get better?

00:49:55.700 --> 00:49:59.930
Just thinking that things could
change to get back to normal

00:49:59.930 --> 00:50:03.470
can be an impetus to start
that process happening.

00:50:03.470 --> 00:50:05.630
In the same way
that if you've gone

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:07.850
through an extended
recovery that's

00:50:07.850 --> 00:50:11.060
created tremendous
excess in the economy,

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:13.820
just people starting to worry
that things go back to normal

00:50:13.820 --> 00:50:17.330
could be enough to
slow the speculation,

00:50:17.330 --> 00:50:20.744
slow price increases and
bring things back to normal.

00:50:20.744 --> 00:50:22.160
Those are things
you don't usually

00:50:22.160 --> 00:50:25.670
read in books about
great value investors

00:50:25.670 --> 00:50:30.680
that I think can really help
refine a value approach.

00:50:30.680 --> 00:50:34.370
And like I say, I think
I learn more reading

00:50:34.370 --> 00:50:39.410
about how great investors
who weren't value investors

00:50:39.410 --> 00:50:44.840
invested than I do by reading
the 200th book about value

00:50:44.840 --> 00:50:46.554
investing.

