by other investors
that whole time.

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:41.990
I go shopping and I
can't help but see

00:54:41.990 --> 00:54:44.720
what new products are out
and how they're priced

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:46.040
compared to old products.

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:48.260
Or if you're in an
off price store,

00:54:48.260 --> 00:54:50.720
that there's suddenly a
tremendous amount of inventory

00:54:50.720 --> 00:54:52.852
from Nike, and
there wasn't before.

00:54:52.852 --> 00:54:54.060
And does that mean something.

00:54:54.060 --> 00:54:57.500
It's just, I think to be
a successful investor,

00:54:57.500 --> 00:54:59.810
it has to be something
you love so much that you

00:54:59.810 --> 00:55:01.850
can't ever really
turn it off, and you

00:55:01.850 --> 00:55:04.580
don't want to turn it off.

00:55:04.580 --> 00:55:06.890
You get enough
enjoyment from it.

00:55:06.890 --> 00:55:10.520
And it doesn't create
stress in a way

00:55:10.520 --> 00:55:14.030
that you feel you need to
get away from it to relax.

00:55:14.030 --> 00:55:15.762
So those are my days.

00:55:15.762 --> 00:55:17.720
And then every once in
a while, it's traveling.

00:55:17.720 --> 00:55:19.190
It's going out to
meet managements.

00:55:19.190 --> 00:55:22.370
We like to sit across
the table from the CEOs

00:55:22.370 --> 00:55:24.730
and CFOs of the companies
that we're invested in,

00:55:24.730 --> 00:55:27.050
and hear in their own words
what's important to them,

00:55:27.050 --> 00:55:29.740
what their goals are.

00:55:29.740 --> 00:55:31.940
I was out in New
York the past couple

00:55:31.940 --> 00:55:34.190
of days meeting
with the managements

00:55:34.190 --> 00:55:38.020
of a lot of the cable TV
investments that we have.

00:55:38.020 --> 00:55:43.400
We own QVC, the TV and
internet shopping network.

00:55:43.400 --> 00:55:46.550
Charter Communications,
recently meeting

00:55:46.550 --> 00:55:48.260
with the management
and GE, which

00:55:48.260 --> 00:55:52.220
has been a breath of fresh
air, in terms of the change

00:55:52.220 --> 00:55:54.500
at the company, but not
entirely pleasant for us,

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:58.410
because it's been a position
we've owned for a while.

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:03.110
But to us, there's no
substitute for the sitting

00:56:03.110 --> 00:56:05.750
across the table and getting
a feel of what's really

00:56:05.750 --> 00:56:07.740
important to these people.

00:56:07.740 --> 00:56:10.719
And again, along the lines of to
earn an active management fee,

00:56:10.719 --> 00:56:12.260
you've got to be
able to do something

00:56:12.260 --> 00:56:15.590
that a computer can't do.

00:56:15.590 --> 00:56:20.090
After you've interviewed
100 investment--

00:56:20.090 --> 00:56:23.150
100 corporate management
teams, you really

00:56:23.150 --> 00:56:26.420
start to have an ability to
say these guys are really

00:56:26.420 --> 00:56:29.360
above average,
these not so much.

00:56:29.360 --> 00:56:31.820
And you don't have to
be perfect with it,

00:56:31.820 --> 00:56:35.950
but if you can be better than
50/50 at how you bucket them,

00:56:35.950 --> 00:56:38.300
as above average
and below average,

00:56:38.300 --> 00:56:41.780
it can be a tremendous
addition to what's

00:56:41.780 --> 00:56:45.592
largely a quantitative
approach to investing.

00:56:45.592 --> 00:56:47.550
SAURABH MADAAN: I think
your love, and passion,

00:56:47.550 --> 00:56:51.320
and enthusiasm for
investing is very obvious,

00:56:51.320 --> 00:56:53.450
and it's very contagious.

00:56:53.450 --> 00:56:55.940
Thank you so much for sharing
your thoughts with us.

00:56:55.940 --> 00:56:58.315
If you we have any last minute
questions in the audience,

00:56:58.315 --> 00:56:59.200
we're open.

00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:00.990
I'll just repeat the question.

00:57:00.990 --> 00:57:03.710
There was this talk about is
there a bubble in the market,

00:57:03.710 --> 00:57:06.140
everything seemed overvalued.

00:57:06.140 --> 00:57:08.670
Other people are making a
lot of money out of bitcoin.

00:57:08.670 --> 00:57:11.850
And what do we do right now?

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:13.670
BILL NYGREN: So we're
generally in the camp

00:57:13.670 --> 00:57:16.490
that if you can't understand
how something is priced,

00:57:16.490 --> 00:57:18.790
it's better not
to talk about it.

00:57:18.790 --> 00:57:22.010
But intellectually, I'm more
in the camp with Jamie Dimon,

00:57:22.010 --> 00:57:25.010
that I have a very hard
time understanding why

00:57:25.010 --> 00:57:28.040
Bitcoin is valued
at whatever price

00:57:28.040 --> 00:57:30.280
it ends up being valued at.

00:57:30.280 --> 00:57:35.330
And you're not going to find
it in the Oakmark portfolios.

00:57:35.330 --> 00:57:41.540
I don't think markets today
are in bubble territory.

00:57:41.540 --> 00:57:44.960
P/Es are only slightly
higher than they've averaged

00:57:44.960 --> 00:57:47.270
in the past 30 or 40 years.

00:57:47.270 --> 00:57:48.980
And I think with
interest rates as low

00:57:48.980 --> 00:57:53.810
as they are, inflation as low as
it is, it makes sense that P/Es

00:57:53.810 --> 00:57:56.450
would be somewhat elevated.

00:57:56.450 --> 00:58:01.460
Not to mention the things like
all the technology companies

00:58:01.460 --> 00:58:05.630
that are making so many
investments in areas tangential

00:58:05.630 --> 00:58:08.450
to their basic business,
that are depressing

00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:09.620
current earnings.

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:14.420
And one of the statistics I put
in the last commentary we wrote

00:58:14.420 --> 00:58:18.800
was that if the four FANG
stocks weren't in the S&amp;P 500,

00:58:18.800 --> 00:58:22.470
the S&amp;P multiple would be
about a point and a half lower.

00:58:22.470 --> 00:58:25.400
Which when you're talking
about a multiple that's maybe

00:58:25.400 --> 00:58:27.920
two or three points elevated
relative to history,

00:58:27.920 --> 00:58:30.210
a point and half is a big deal.

00:58:30.210 --> 00:58:32.120
And I don't take
the stocks out just

00:58:32.120 --> 00:58:34.370
because they look
expensive on a P/E basis,

00:58:34.370 --> 00:58:38.870
but P/E is such a bad metric
for measuring the value

00:58:38.870 --> 00:58:41.180
of those four companies.

00:58:41.180 --> 00:58:43.970
So we don't think the
market's really elevated.

00:58:43.970 --> 00:58:47.090
You know, the recovery's
nine years old.

00:58:47.090 --> 00:58:48.920
But the magnitude
of the recovery

00:58:48.920 --> 00:58:53.540
has been relatively trivial
compared to historic growth

00:58:53.540 --> 00:58:54.860
of the economy.

00:58:54.860 --> 00:58:57.920
Recessions come about to
correct excesses in the economy.

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:01.670
It's hard to see those
excesses being created.

00:59:01.670 --> 00:59:04.190
To me, the more fascinating
part of your question

00:59:04.190 --> 00:59:08.210
is how do you deal with
a bubble like 2000,

00:59:08.210 --> 00:59:11.360
where a strict
discipline valuation

00:59:11.360 --> 00:59:14.780
approach to investing just
says none of these names

00:59:14.780 --> 00:59:15.840
make sense to us.

00:59:15.840 --> 00:59:18.100
We can't figure out the values.

00:59:18.100 --> 00:59:21.120
And how do you keep
people invested with you

00:59:21.120 --> 00:59:25.360
when you're holding the line
that says these names just

00:59:25.360 --> 00:59:27.040
don't make sense.

00:59:27.040 --> 00:59:30.040
The Oakmark fund assets
peaked at about $10 billion

00:59:30.040 --> 00:59:34.132
in 1997, '98.

00:59:34.132 --> 00:59:35.590
And even though
our net asset value

00:59:35.590 --> 00:59:40.060
had been about flat for
the following two years,

00:59:40.060 --> 00:59:42.520
our assets were
down to $2 billion.

00:59:42.520 --> 00:59:44.500
Because we refused
to buy anything

00:59:44.500 --> 00:59:47.920
in the technology space, people
took 80% of the investments

00:59:47.920 --> 00:59:49.660
away from us.

00:59:49.660 --> 00:59:52.534
And that's a tremendously
difficult time

00:59:52.534 --> 00:59:54.700
when you're running a
business and you've got people

00:59:54.700 --> 00:59:57.850
to employ, that you want
to have continue with you,

00:59:57.850 --> 00:59:59.800
and you're seeing your
revenues fall by 80%.

01:00:02.410 --> 01:00:05.140
I remember at a
conference call I was on.

01:00:05.140 --> 01:00:09.370
One of the advisors who was
in the process of selling out

01:00:09.370 --> 01:00:12.400
of the fund, was
pleading with me, saying

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:14.620
won't you please just
on one technology stock,

01:00:14.620 --> 01:00:16.120
because if you buy
one of them, then

01:00:16.120 --> 01:00:17.830
I can go back to my
investment committee

01:00:17.830 --> 01:00:19.930
and tell them that's OK.

01:00:19.930 --> 01:00:22.420
And I remember saying
to her, I said,

01:00:22.420 --> 01:00:25.270
if we could find one that
fit our value criteria,

01:00:25.270 --> 01:00:28.120
we'd happily own
it, but we can't.

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:29.934
And because of that we won't.

01:00:29.934 --> 01:00:31.600
I said, and I'll bet
you something else.

01:00:31.600 --> 01:00:34.180
There is going to be
a time in the future

01:00:34.180 --> 01:00:36.970
that you're going to say
it's not that Oakmark's

01:00:36.970 --> 01:00:41.740
incapable of buying technology,
but when technology is out

01:00:41.740 --> 01:00:44.140
of favor, we're going to
own more than the market

01:00:44.140 --> 01:00:45.830
weighting in it.

01:00:45.830 --> 01:00:47.590
And I said, you're
probably going

01:00:47.590 --> 01:00:50.350
to be just as upset with
us then as you are now.

01:00:50.350 --> 01:00:52.360
Because we're investing
in something then

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:54.550
that would be unpopular.

01:00:54.550 --> 01:00:56.480
And it's tough.

01:00:56.480 --> 01:00:59.580
But if you don't stick
to your discipline--

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:01.420
there was a Chicago
firm that was

01:01:01.420 --> 01:01:05.050
known more for growth
investing that was still

01:01:05.050 --> 01:01:07.480
a pretty strong
fundamental value firm,

01:01:07.480 --> 01:01:10.120
but they applied it
to growth stocks.

01:01:10.120 --> 01:01:16.100
And about February of 2000, they
threw in the towel, and said,

01:01:16.100 --> 01:01:17.680
we've lost too many
of our investors,

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:19.660
we're going to start
buying these very high

01:01:19.660 --> 01:01:21.610
priced internet names,
even though they

01:01:21.610 --> 01:01:24.580
don't work under the
way we used to invest.

01:01:24.580 --> 01:01:26.140
So they didn't
ride the market up.

01:01:26.140 --> 01:01:27.460
They rode it all the way down.

01:01:27.460 --> 01:01:29.950
And it put their
firm out of business.

01:01:29.950 --> 01:01:33.370
You mentioned earlier, I was
named Morningstar Manager

01:01:33.370 --> 01:01:35.860
of the Year in 2001.

01:01:35.860 --> 01:01:39.220
It wasn't that we did anything
different in 2001 than we

01:01:39.220 --> 01:01:42.760
did in 2000, or '99, or '99.

01:01:42.760 --> 01:01:46.870
It was the market suddenly
corrected valuation excesses.

01:01:46.870 --> 01:01:49.120
And the traditional
companies we'd

01:01:49.120 --> 01:01:52.030
owned through this whole
period went up in price

01:01:52.030 --> 01:01:56.110
significantly, while all the
tech names came crashing down.

01:01:56.110 --> 01:01:59.740
But it was the discipline
to say we're going

01:01:59.740 --> 01:02:01.950
to keep doing the same thing.

01:02:01.950 --> 01:02:03.820
And we know if
we're fundamentally

01:02:03.820 --> 01:02:07.950
right on the analysis, the stock
prices will eventually follow.

01:02:07.950 --> 01:02:10.840
And we're not going
to try and placate

01:02:10.840 --> 01:02:16.360
investors who want to see us
invest in the current bubble.

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:20.470
I remember being
on CNBC back then,

01:02:20.470 --> 01:02:24.580
talking about how high priced we
thought technology names were.

01:02:24.580 --> 01:02:28.792
And I hopped into a cab
on my way home from work.

01:02:28.792 --> 01:02:31.000
And I can see the cab driver
looking in his rear view

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:34.450
mirror, and he's like
I think I know you.

01:02:34.450 --> 01:02:35.060
And I'm like--

01:02:35.060 --> 01:02:37.900
I kind of got my head down, and
I'm like no, I don't think so.

01:02:37.900 --> 01:02:39.310
He was like, yeah, yeah, I do.

01:02:39.310 --> 01:02:42.121
I've seen you on TV.

01:02:42.121 --> 01:02:43.780
And I'm like maybe.

01:02:43.780 --> 01:02:45.730
He's like, you're
that guy on CNBC.

01:02:45.730 --> 01:02:49.932
And my portfolio's
kicking your butt.

01:02:49.932 --> 01:02:52.390
And I'm like, you know what,
it's not that far to my house,

01:02:52.390 --> 01:02:53.890
why don't you just
drop me off here,

01:02:53.890 --> 01:02:55.720
I'll walk the rest of the way.

01:02:55.720 --> 01:02:59.710
But when things
get that popular,

01:02:59.710 --> 01:03:03.310
it's very rare that they end
up being good investments.

01:03:03.310 --> 01:03:06.740
And as long term
value investors,

01:03:06.740 --> 01:03:09.460
we get a lot of comfort
from the history

01:03:09.460 --> 01:03:12.130
of seeing bubbles
grow and bubbles pop.

01:03:12.130 --> 01:03:16.570
And the people who
whether those bubbles

01:03:16.570 --> 01:03:20.860
well are the ones who had a
philosophy that grounded them

01:03:20.860 --> 01:03:25.035
and they didn't change it to
reflect bubble level pricing.

01:03:27.254 --> 01:03:28.920
SAURABH MADAAN: Well,
thank you so much.

01:03:28.920 --> 01:03:31.320
Really appreciate all the
time that you took being here.

01:03:31.320 --> 01:03:32.610
BILL NYGREN: Great, thank you.

01:03:32.610 --> 01:03:34.730
Thank you all.

